{
  "text": "The development of a dipole model for EMI sensing of conducting and/or ferrous targets has been discussed in detail elsewhere [CITATION_1] , [CITATION_2] . We here summarize the model to elucidate which parameters will be sought in the search process. In the coordinate system of the sensor, the z direction is normal to the air-soil interface and the z-component of magnetic field is measured. In addition, assume that the magnetic dipole of the source current is also z-directed, corresponding to the coil configuration in Fig. 1 . For a unitstrength source dipole, the z-directed magnetic field induced by the presence of a targets is represented as [CITATION_3] , [CITATION_4] H z \u00f0\u00c2jr r r r s ; ! s \u00de \u00bc z \u00c0 z s \u00bd\u00f0r r r r \u00c0 r r r r s \u00de T \u00f0r r r r \u00c0 r r s \u00de 3 \u00f0r r \u00c0 r r s \u00de T U U T M M\u00f0! s \u00deU U\u00f0r r \u00c0 r r s \u00de; \u00f01\u00de where r r s \u00bc \u00bdx s ; y s ; z s T is the position vector of the sensordipole, ! s is the sensor transmission frequency (in Hertz), r r \u00bc \u00bdx; y; z T is the position vector of the target-dipole, and the dipole target is characterized by the 3 \u00c2 3 diagonal magnetization tensor",
  "correct_citation": {
